The ORNL 3-MV Van de Graaff accelerator
The neutrons were produced by using the
7Li(p,n) and
T(p,n) reactions with thick targets and
the proton energy adjusted to cover the neutron
energy ranges 7-70 keV and 20-170 keV, respectively.
Fast (nano-second) time-of-flight techniques.
Time spectra were obtained for the various samples,
with an indium (standard) sample being run approxim.
every fourth time, or about once every 15 minutes.
another
similar experiment.
The natural element samples used to date have been 5-
to 7-inch diameter disks. Metals were used where
possible. Pressed oxides and lead salts in thin
(0.001 in.) evacuated iron cans were used when
necessary. The sample thickness was chosen to give
1/E attenuation for about 150-keV gamma rays, and to
limit the neutron scattering to a few percent.

Considerable effort was therefore expended in
determining the shape of the indium capture cross
section relative to the shape of the total
absorption cross section of U-235 above 100 keV, and
relative to the shape of the 10B(n,alpha1+gamma)7Li
cross section below 140 keV.
For this goal additional experiments were made
(see description in PR,122,182,1961).
The absolute value of the indium capture
cross section was normalized to its values for
threshold neutrons (30 and 65 keV) (see Subent 106)

0.free_text: The weighted indium cross section resulting from normalization at 30 keV was defined. (see REL-REF) * The capture cross section of indium at 65 keV was obtained by measuring the ratio of the 65 to 30 keV cross sections. * The indium capture cross section at 167 keV was determined by normalizing the relative indium cross section versus neutron energy curve at 30 and 65 keV and reading the value as measured by the shape of the U-235 absorption cross section.

free_txt: An estimated typical standard deviation.
It includes:
The absolute (standard deviation) error in the
value of the cross section standard at has been
indicated to be about 6%. (The weighted indium cross
section resulting from normalization at 30 keV as
described in the article)
* For the measurement of the cross section of other
samples relative to the indium standard, at the
threshold energies, 30 and 65 keV, other sources
of error must be considered:
The error in the determination of the net area
under the time spectrum peak is estimated to be about
5% except where noted.
The uncertainties in calculating the R.S.P.
(resonance self-protection) correction for the sample
the relative to indium, as discussed in Appendix III
of article (PR,122,182,1961) , are estimated to be
of order 2%.
The uncertainties in the tank efficiency for
a sample as compared to indium are determined by two
considerations. The total efficiency error is
assigned to be 5%.
The uncertainty in the average path-length
correction as discussed in Appendix II of the article
* The uncertainties in sample weight and geometry
are negligible.
The best five of these measurements, with their
standard deviations, were used to provide normalization
for the present experiment in the following manner:
The capture tank measurements of the shapes of the
five cross sections as a function of neutron energy
were used to extend the spherical shell cross
sections to 30 keV. Then shell transmission
